Data released by the Nigerian Bureau of Statistics (NBS) has revealed that 179.17 million subscribers were active on voice in third quarter 2019 as against 174.02 million in second quarter 2019 and 162.03 million in Q3 2018. According to the statistics on Telecoms Data: Active Voice and internet per state, porting and tariff information released yesterday, the number of voice subscribers increased by 2.96 per cent Quarter-on-Quarter (QoQ) and 10.58 per cent year on year.Â  Similarly, a total of 123.16 million subscribers were active on internet as against 122.67 million in Q2 2019 and 103.51 million in Q3 2018. This represented 0.40 per cent growth in internet subscriptions quarter on quarter and 18.98 per cent year-on-year (Y-o-Y). The report further stated that Lagos state has the highest number of subscribers in terms of active voice per state in Q3 2019 and closely followed by Ogun and Kano states respectively while Bayelsa and Ebonyi states have the least number of subscribers. Also, Lagos state has the highest number of subscribers in terms of active internet per state in Q3 2019 and closely followed by Ogun and Kano states respectively while Bayelsa and Ebonyi states have the least number of subscribers. It further disclosed that MTN had the highest share of voice subscription, closely followed by Glo, Airtel, EMTS and others respectively. Similarly, MTN has the highest share of internet subscription and followed by Airtel, Glo, EMTS and others.